## LLM API Integration

NEPA-HRI wraps any LLM (Claude, GPT-4o, Gemini) by injecting a
stability context block into the system prompt:

```python
from simulator.metrics import p_escalation, t_recover, feeling_load, volatility_index

# Compute AML context from your interaction trace
aml_context = {
    "metrics": {
        "volatility_index":    round(float(VI[t]),   3),
        "stability_index":     round(float(S[t]),    3),
        "augmentation_score":  round(float(AS[t]),   3),
        "feeling_load":        round(float(F[t]),    3),
        "affective_pred_error":round(float(delta[t]),3),
    },
    "envelope": {
        "kappa":        1.8,
        "inside_omega": bool(abs(delta[t]) <= 1.8 * S[t]),
        "regime":       "A_stable" if abs(delta[t]) <= 1.8*S[t] else "B_escalation",
    },
    "recommended_action": "LOCAL_HANDLE" if abs(delta[t]) <= 1.8*S[t] else "ESCALATE"
}

# Inject into LLM system prompt
system_prompt = f"""
You are an interaction-aware AI assistant.
You receive a stability context block from the NEPA-HRI Affective Modulation Layer.
Use it to calibrate your response tone and strategy.

Current AML context:
{aml_context}

Rules:
- If regime is A_stable: respond normally, maintain engagement.
- If regime is B_escalation: de-escalate, be concise, reduce complexity.
- Never label user emotions directly.
- Never override a ESCALATE recommended_action — flag for human operator instead.
- Keep all responses within the stability envelope.
"""
```

This gives your LLM a grounded, auditable, bounded control signal —
not free-floating language intuition.

